We will use a Poppler-free method.


---

âœ… Easiest Method (No Poppler): Use PyMuPDF (fitz)

This library can read PDF pages directly and produce images that EasyOCR can read.

Step 1 â€” Install these packages

Open VS Code terminal:

pip install pymupdf easyocr pillow

That's it.
No Poppler. No system PATH.
Works on all laptops.


---

âœ… Step 2 â€” Use This Code (PDF â†’ OCR Without Poppler)

import fitz  # PyMuPDF
import easyocr
from PIL import Image
import io

pdf_path = "your.pdf"

reader = easyocr.Reader(['en'])
full_text = ""

doc = fitz.open(pdf_path)

for page_num in range(len(doc)):
    page = doc[page_num]

    # Render page as image
    pix = page.get_pixmap()
    img_bytes = pix.tobytes("png")
    img = Image.open(io.BytesIO(img_bytes))

    img.save(f"page_{page_num}.png")

    # OCR the image
    text = reader.readtext(f"page_{page_num}.png", detail=0)
    full_text += "\n".join(text) + "\n"

print(full_text)

This works perfectly for:

âœ” Any PDF
âœ” Multi-page PDFs
âœ” PDFs you created from Word
âœ” Scanned PDFs

And most importantly:

âŒ No Poppler needed
âŒ No PATH setup
âŒ No external software install


